<h1>Travel Nurse Taxes in Florida 2026</h1>
<p class="hub-crumb" style="font-family:sans-serif;font-size:0.9em;background:#f0f4ff;border-left:4px solid #3b6cf8;padding:8px 14px;border-radius:0 6px 6px 0;margin:14px 0;">Part of the <a href="travel-nurse-tax-hub-2026.html"><strong>Travel Nurse Tax Hub</strong></a> &mdash; browse every related guide in one place.</p>
<p style="font-size:1.15em;color:#444">Like Texas, Florida has no state income tax — which makes it both a tax-friendly place to take assignments and a popular domicile for travel nurses. Here's how Florida assignments are taxed, how stipends stay tax-free, and why so many travelers make Florida their home base.</p>

<div class="warning">
<strong>Not tax advice.</strong> General educational information only. Travel nurse taxes are fact-specific; consult a tax professional who understands travel healthcare before filing.
</div>

<h2>No State Income Tax in Florida</h2>
<p>Florida is one of the states with no personal state income tax. On a Florida travel assignment, the taxable wage portion of your contract is subject only to federal income tax and FICA — no Florida state income tax at all. On the same bill rate, that means more take-home than a high-tax state. It's also why Florida is one of the most popular <em>domicile</em> states for travelers: keep a legitimate Florida tax home and your home-sourced income escapes state income tax.</p>

<h2>Wages vs. Stipends: The Federal Split Still Applies</h2>
<p>No state income tax doesn't change how the federal government treats your pay. A travel contract divides pay into a taxable hourly wage and non-taxable reimbursements (housing, meals, incidentals). Those stipends are tax-free only if you maintain a genuine tax home and work temporarily away from it.</p>
<table>
<tr><th>Pay Component</th><th>Tax Treatment (Florida assignment)</th></tr>
<tr><td>Hourly taxable wage</td><td>Federal income tax + FICA; no Florida state income tax</td></tr>
<tr><td>Housing stipend</td><td>Tax-free federally <em>only</em> with a valid tax home</td></tr>
<tr><td>Meals &amp; incidentals (M&amp;IE)</td><td>Tax-free under the same condition</td></tr>
<tr><td>Travel reimbursement</td><td>Generally non-taxable when documented</td></tr>
</table>

<h2>Tax Home: The Rule That Protects Your Stipends</h2>
<p>Your tax home is generally the place where you maintain a permanent residence and to which you regularly return. Stipends stay tax-free only if you're <strong>duplicating living expenses</strong> — paying for a home base <em>and</em> paying for lodging on assignment. Without a legitimate tax home, the IRS treats you as itinerant and your stipends become taxable wages.</p>

<div class="callout">
<strong>Florida as your domicile:</strong> Because Florida has no state income tax and is easy to establish residency in (driver's license, vehicle registration, voter registration, a declaration of domicile in some counties), many travelers make Florida their home base. Done legitimately — you actually maintain and return to a Florida residence — it can mean no state income tax on your home-sourced income while assignment states tax only the wages earned there.
</div>

<h2>The 12-Month Rule</h2>
<p>The IRS generally treats a work location as "temporary" only when the assignment is realistically expected to last a year or less. Stay in the same Florida metro — Miami, Tampa, Orlando, Jacksonville — continuously beyond roughly 12 months and the IRS can deem it your new tax home, making stipends there taxable. Rotating locations and taking breaks before returning to the same area keeps assignments clearly temporary.</p>

<h2>Records to Keep</h2>
<table>
<tr><th>Document</th><th>Why It Matters</th></tr>
<tr><td>Proof of permanent residence costs</td><td>Rent/mortgage, utilities — shows a duplicated tax home</td></tr>
<tr><td>Contracts &amp; agency pay stubs</td><td>Shows wage/stipend split and dates</td></tr>
<tr><td>Lodging receipts on assignment</td><td>Confirms duplicated expenses</td></tr>
<tr><td>Mileage &amp; travel logs</td><td>Supports travel reimbursements and return trips</td></tr>
<tr><td>Florida license, registration, voter record</td><td>Supports a Florida domicile if you claim one</td></tr>
</table>

<h2>Practical Florida Takeaways</h2>
<p>Florida's no-income-tax status makes it both a favorable place to take contracts and a top domicile choice for travel nurses. But the federal tax-home requirement that makes stipends tax-free applies no matter which state you work in, so protect your tax home carefully and don't overstay one metro past the 12-month zone. If you're picking a home base, a legitimate Florida domicile is one of the most common and effective choices. A travel-savvy tax preparer will help you set it up correctly.</p>

<h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
<p><strong>Do I pay state income tax on a Florida assignment?</strong> No — Florida has no personal state income tax. You still owe federal income tax and FICA on the taxable wage.</p>
<p><strong>Are my stipends tax-free in Florida?</strong> Tax-free federally only if you maintain a valid tax home and work temporarily away from it. No state income tax doesn't remove that federal requirement.</p>
<p><strong>Why do travelers pick Florida as a home base?</strong> No state income tax plus relatively straightforward residency requirements make it a popular, legitimate domicile — when you actually maintain a Florida home.</p>

